Comparative evidence shows that in India, women is squarely liable for child related matters and, despite their often reduced decision making abilities, have full responsibility for their child if they decide to go ahead with the pregnancy without concealing it from their spouse. Conversely, in the Urban Juju Valley, while the couples have the same access to social and professional networks to enable them to hide secret pregnancies from their spouses, men have no reciprocal rights in terms of decisions on child related matters.

The law itself is yet to effectively check the practice of infanticide. As I explained in my earlier work in another area of customary law and women’s agency, the murrabitoun law empowers the father to provide evidence to the judge to “exclude” the child from inheritance; although in theory the mother suspicious of infanticide can testify to the judge that the child had been thrown into a well, in practice this is very difficult and rare. I further speculate that where unregistered bachelors or clandestine marriages are more common, it may make little difference what the wife claims to the murrabitoun, and the father can still claim infanticide to exclude the child.
